Title : Jacques Borker
Text : '''Jacques Borker''' (born 1922 in [[Paris]], [[France]]) is a [[French artist]] and is the most influential and one of the best known tapestry designers of the twentieth century.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nazmiyal|first=J.|title=French Art Deco Carpet by Jacques Borker 47511|url=http://nazmiyalantiquerugs.com/antique-rugs/art-deco/french-art-deco-carpet-jacques-borker-47511/|publisher=Nazmiyal Collection|accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref> Borker has long been admired for his fantastic [[Abstract art|abstract]], [[art deco]] and contemporary tapestry designs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Masteau|first=Pierre|title=Au Carré du Perche, ils seront 21 à exposer : pastelliste, peintres, sculpteurs et céramistes|url=http://www.forumarts61.com/blog/2013/02/au-carre-du-perche-ils-seront-21-a-exposer-pastelliste-peintres-sculpteurs-et-ceramistes|publisher=Forum des Arts 61|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>
Working out of Paris during some of the most important art movements of the era, Borker is known for his bold interpretation of the abstract, as well as for his mastery of line work.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nazmiyal|first=J.|title=French Art Deco Carpet by Jacques Borker 47511|url=http://nazmiyalantiquerugs.com/antique-rugs/art-deco/french-art-deco-carpet-jacques-borker-47511/|publisher=Nazmiyal Collection|accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dm|first=Van|title=Vintage 1960s French Design Studio Art Carpet by Jacques Borker|url=http://www.polyvore.com/vintage_1960s_french_design_studio/thing?id=71843931|publisher=Polyvore|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref> Borker's work is most associated with [[Bauhaus]] and the [[Art Deco]] art movement.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Raspail|first1=Atelier|title=Jacques Borker|url=http://atelier-raspail.com/Peinture_Home_Jacques_Borker_2.html|publisher=L'Atelier Raspail|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>

==Biography==
Borker studied various artistic disciplines including [[architecture]] at [[Ecole des Beaux Arts]], where he was a contemporary and friend of [[Le Corbusier]], [[Charlotte Perriand]], [[Jean Lurçat]], [[Zao Wou-Ki]], [[Pierre Soulages]] and [[Hans Hartung]]. He also studied [[Ceramic art]], [[tapestry]] and [[industrial design]].

During [[World War II]], Borker was involved in the [[Liberation of France|liberation]] of [[Toulouse]] and was active in the [[French resistance]].

Borker's work has been exhibited at art galleries and museums in many cities around the world.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sper|first=Art|title=Jacques Borker France Biography|url=http://www.artsper.com/artistes-contemporains/france/871/jacques-borker?lan=en|publisher=Artsper|accessdate=24 April 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429183619/http://www.artsper.com/artistes-contemporains/france/871/jacques-borker?lan=en|archivedate=29 April 2014|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fontenel|first=Aline|title=Jacques Borker l'artiste|url=http://www.borkerjacques.fr/#!presse/c20p0|publisher=L'Art demain|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Masteau|first=Pierre|title=Jacques Borker|url=http://www.borkerjacques.fr/#!presse/c20p0|work=Critique d'Art 1967|publisher=Critique d'Art|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Courbier|first=Benoît|title=Jacques Borker Critique d'Art|url=http://www.borkerjacques.fr/#!presse/c20p0|publisher=Jacques Borker Presse|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Païni|first=Dominique|title=Jacques Borker Artiste|url=http://www.borkerjacques.fr/#!presse/c20p0|publisher=Jacques Borker Presse|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dm|first=Van|title=Vintage 1960s French Design Studio Art Carpet by Jacques Borker|url=http://www.polyvore.com/vintage_1960s_french_design_studio/thing?id=71843931|publisher=Polyvore|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Borker|first=Jacques|title=Parcours|url=http://www.borkerjacques.fr/#!parcours/cjs3|publisher=borkerjacques.fr|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>

Borker is the brother of [[Jules Borker]], the French [[Human rights|human rights lawyer]] and former [[Secretary-General]] of the Paris
branch of the French [[Bar Association]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Sirach|first=Marie-José|title=Jules Borker, une vie de résistance à toute injustice|url=https://www.humanite.fr/jules-borker-une-vie-de-resistance-toute-injustice|publisher=L'humanité France|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Puig de la Bellacasa|first=José María|title=Un resistente|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/obituarios/20140407/54405586259/jules-borker-resistente.html|publisher=Lavanguardia|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Tiersky|first=Ronald|title=The French Co|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O3SI6YJA_8wC&pg=PA243 |publisher=Columbia University Press|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Laurent|first=Pierre|title=Décès de Jules Borker : "la disparition d'un acteur de son temps " (Pierre Laurent)|url=https://www.humanite.fr/fil-rouge/deces-de-jules-borker-la-disparition-dun-acteur-de-son-temps-pierre-laurent|publisher=L'humanité France|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Valeanu|first=Richard|title=Jules Borker (1919-2014)|url=http://www.valeanu.com/?p=269|publisher=Valeanu|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>

==Impact==
It has been said that for the first time in France during the second half of the twentieth century, due to Borker's work, architecture, painting and design are met in France with grace and harmony. Furthermore, Borker's creative research using simple everyday materials and bright colours has been quoted as "a pleasure for the eye" and his work has given a "certain elegance to late 20th century French art".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Raspail|first1=Atelier|title=Jacques Borker|url=http://atelier-raspail.com/Peinture_Home_Jacques_Borker_2.html|publisher=L'Atelier Raspail|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Jacques Borker was married to [[Paulette Borker]], who was also involved with the [[French resistance]] during [[World War II]].{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}

Borker currently resides in the Parisian street [[Rue de Seine]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Association|first=des anciens eleves de l'ecole nationale d'administration|title=La décentralisation, n°431, Mai 2013|url=http://www.aaeena.fr/publications/la-revue/lena-hors-les-murs-revue-de-lassociation-des-anciens-eleves-de-lena/la-decentralisation-ndeg431-mai-2013|publisher=association des anciens eleves de l'ecole nationale d'administration|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>

